<div id="review_525575351" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/525575351" />
    <a title="Elaine Tomaschik" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7308728-elaine-tomaschik"><img alt="Elaine Tomaschik" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1325488196p2/7308728.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/525575351?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elaine Tomaschik" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elaine Tomaschik" href="/user/show/7308728-elaine-tomaschik">Elaine Tomaschik</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer525575351" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8660595540854918375">Excellent book that inspires conflicting feelings about the protagonist. You have to love Ase for his goodness and &apos;complicated simplicity&apos; but there were times when I wanted to shake him for his seeming indifference (more accurately his inaction). But I came to understand that was his nature, and maybe you don&apos;t really understand that until the very end of the book. It&apos;s a wonderful study in human nature where all characters are concerned, especially in the interactions. Rawlings&apos; character dev</span>
  <span id="freeText8660595540854918375" style="display:none">Excellent book that inspires conflicting feelings about the protagonist. You have to love Ase for his goodness and 'complicated simplicity' but there were times when I wanted to shake him for his seeming indifference (more accurately his inaction). But I came to understand that was his nature, and maybe you don't really understand that until the very end of the book. It's a wonderful study in human nature where all characters are concerned, especially in the interactions. Rawlings' character development is extraordinary, as are her depictions. This book has a lot of detail regarding surroundings and every day life -- a plus for those who enjoy such things, a minus for those who can do without and just want to 'get on with the story.'<br />I'm somewhere in between, although I think the many descriptors only help to understand the depths of Ase.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8660595540854918375" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


