  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1968014996" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1968014996" />
    <a title="Carol Bakker" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2534237-carol-bakker"><img alt="Carol Bakker" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1337830449p2/2534237.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1968014996?book_show_action=true">May 15, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carol Bakker" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carol Bakker" href="/user/show/2534237-carol-bakker">Carol Bakker</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781849024945" href="/book/show/11626101-the-sojourner">review of another edition</a>


          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Carol Bakker by: </span>
      Janie Dye
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2534237-carol-bakker?shelf=work">work</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2534237-carol-bakker?shelf=grim">grim</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2534237-carol-bakker?shelf=2017">2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2534237-carol-bakker?shelf=culture">culture</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2534237-carol-bakker?shelf=family">family</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2534237-carol-bakker?shelf=literary">literary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2534237-carol-bakker?shelf=agriculture">agriculture</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1968014996" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10158140060478144571"><i>The Sojourner</i> was a dreadful book. By that, I mean reading it filled me with dread. <br/><br/>At its core are two brothers and a mother. One son she adores; the other she deplores. The mother <i>was second generation Scotch-Irish, with all of the Scot dourness and none of the Irish lilt.</i> There is nothing fair about Amelia, relative to beauty and justice. <br/><br/>Rawlings compelled me to respect and love the protagonist, Asahel Linden. I wanted to shield him from psychological desolation brought on by <i>the strangers i</i></span>
  <span id="freeText10158140060478144571" style="display:none"><i>The Sojourner</i> was a dreadful book. By that, I mean reading it filled me with dread. <br /><br />At its core are two brothers and a mother. One son she adores; the other she deplores. The mother <i>was second generation Scotch-Irish, with all of the Scot dourness and none of the Irish lilt.</i> There is nothing fair about Amelia, relative to beauty and justice. <br /><br />Rawlings compelled me to respect and love the protagonist, Asahel Linden. I wanted to shield him from psychological desolation brought on by <i>the strangers in his family</i>. With one bright exception, he lives with disdain and disregard from his close relatives. The author nails emotional estrangement of father and sons. The distant father is a common trope; Rawlings upends that with unreachable sons. <br /><br />Enter: dread. I had to close the book for two weeks before I could continue. It reminded me of reading Steinbeck's <i>East of Eden</i>, which I had to force myself to finish because I anticipated the ending of Cain and Abel.<br /><br />Agrarian wisdom is scattered like seeds throughout the pages. Written in 1953, (pre-Wendell Berry) it breathes economy and husbandry, respect for animals and a refusal to despoil the land. <br /><br />The ending was not as I predicted; it left me wistful, made me sigh. The writing is remarkably resplendent. She can turn a phrase, describe people, landscapes, situations and emotions with fresh vigor. <br /><br />Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings has risen on my list of authors to read. <br /><br />4.5 stars<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10158140060478144571" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

