  <span id="freeText3823885018859057890" style="display:none">I loved it. It was an escape into a world 100 years ago. I could see a movie in my head as I read this book. Leo DiCaprio could play the brother Benjamin. Ase's character will stay with me forever. He was a very good man. I loved how the chapters of his life reflected the technologies - how fast it all changed from him driving a horse and buggy to driving a car to the airplane at the very end. The dynamic between his mother and brother is all too familar - a dysfunctional abusive family. I loved the struggles he had with his children, he didnt like all of them! The way the missed opportunities were articulated...with father and son/daughters -- he stayed silent. He never lost his bond with his brother and in the end they were together. I didnt like the ending; but like water under the bridge - things always end. This book will stay in my heart. Like life itself, the book went way too fast. </span>
